#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:5
msgid "Summary"
msgstr "摘要"

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:7
msgid ""
"The rules about the places `mod foo;` can be used are tightened to only "
"permit its use in a crate root and in `mod.rs` files, to ensure a more sane "
"correspondence between module structure and file system hierarchy. Most "
"notably, this prevents a common newbie error where a module is loaded "
"multiple times, leading to surprising incompatibility between them. This "
"proposal does not take away one's ability to shoot oneself in the foot "
"should one really desire to; it just removes almost all of the rope, leaving "
"only mixed metaphors."
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:16
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr "動機"

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:18
msgid "It is a common newbie mistake to write things like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:20
msgid "`lib.rs`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:27
msgid "`foo.rs`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:35
msgid "`bar.rs`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:46
msgid "`baz.rs`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:52
msgid ""
"This fails to compile because `foo::foo()` wants a `foo::baz::Baz`, while "
"`bar::bar()` is giving it a `bar::baz::Baz`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:55
msgid ""
"Such a situation, importing one file multiple times, is exceedingly rarely "
"what the user actually wanted to do, but the present design allows it to "
"occur without warning the user. The alterations contained herein ensure that "
"there is no situation where such double loading can occur without deliberate "
"intent via `#[path = \"….rs\"]`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:61
msgid "Drawbacks"
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:63
msgid "None known."
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:65
msgid "Detailed design"
msgstr "詳細設計"

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:67
msgid ""
"When a `mod foo;` statement is used, the compiler attempts to find a "
"suitable file. At present, it just blindly seeks for `foo.rs` or `foo/mod."
"rs` (relative to the file under parsing)."
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:71
msgid ""
"The new behaviour will only permit `mod foo;` if at least one of the "
"following conditions hold:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:74
msgid "The file under parsing is the crate root, or"
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:76
msgid "The file under parsing is a `mod.rs`, or"
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:78
msgid "`#[path]` is specified, e.g. `#[path = \"foo.rs\"] mod foo;`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:80
msgid ""
"In layman's terms, the file under parsing must \"own\" the directory, so to "
"speak."
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:83
msgid "Alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:85
msgid ""
"The rationale is covered in the summary. This is the simplest repair to the "
"current lack of structure; all alternatives would be more complex and "
"invasive."
msgstr ""

#: src/0063-module-file-system-hierarchy.md:88
msgid ""
"One non-invasive alternative is a lint which would detect double loads. This "
"is less desirable than the solution discussed in this RFC as it doesn't fix "
"the underlying problem which can, fortunately, be fairly easily fixed."
msgstr ""

